  <p class="lede">
    Charities delivering aid to humanitarian camps sit on data that could make every delivery
    smarter — and serve people who can least afford to have that data leak. This project was an
    exercise in refusing the usual trade-off: build the intelligence without surrendering the
    information.
  </p>

  <h2>The constraint that shaped everything</h2>
  <p>
    The people relying on this system are among the most vulnerable anywhere. Beneficiary records
    — who they are, where they are, what they need — must never reach third-party services, no
    matter how convenient a cloud API would be. I treated that as a hard architectural constraint
    rather than a compliance afterthought, and it ended up defining the entire design.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Locally hosted language model</strong> — all natural-language capability runs on
      infrastructure the organisation controls. No prompts, records or fragments of beneficiary
      information ever leave it.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Custom predictive model</strong> — trained on the charity’s own historical
      distribution data to anticipate demand across camps, rather than shipping that history to an
      external service.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Recommendations, not automation</strong> — the system gives coordinators allocation
      recommendations they can interrogate and overrule. Human judgement stays in charge of
      decisions that affect lives.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>The result</h2>
  <p>
    The finished system gave coordinators genuinely useful allocation recommendations — where aid
    was likely to be needed, and how to distribute limited supplies — while keeping every piece of
    sensitive information inside the organisation’s walls. It took first place at the IBM ×
    Capital One Hackathon.
  </p>

  <div class="pull">
    The award mattered less than the lesson: capable systems must also be accountable ones. When
    AI serves vulnerable people, privacy is not a feature — it is the design brief.
  </div>

  <h2>What it changed</h2>
  <p>
    This project made responsible AI concrete for me. Principles like data minimisation and local
    control stopped being abstractions and became engineering decisions with real users on the
    other side. It is a large part of why interpretability and safety now sit alongside capability
    in my research interests — and why I want to build AI for the places that need it most,
    on terms that protect the people it serves.
  </p>
</Project>
